Issue

ranks above all degrees. He has
been a true educator, Williams
will miss a gentleman of great
ability and quiet, friendly marl~
ner. Congratulations, Mr. Bow»
en. We know that you will be
a success in your new position
as you were in your much too
brief Stay at Williams.”

Before assuming office July
1, 1955, Bowen visited campus
several times. On April 30 he
addressed an all-college assem-
bly in Herrick Chapel. In his
first official appearance on
campus Bowen offered several
remarks.

“First of all, I want you to
know how pleased and proud I
am to have been invited to join
you here. I have long been an
admirer of Grinneii. In fact, I
first visited the campus just 21

 

years ago this spring, and on
several occasions have attended
conferences here. But I think I
had not fully understood the tub
tent of its reputation until the
flood of mail began pouring in
after my appointment was an-
nounced. I wish that I might
read some of it to you. The con-
sistent theme is that Grinnell
is not just‘another small liberal
arts college. It is a Very special
institution with a unique and
precious heritage.

"I have asked myself: ‘What
accounts for the outstanding
reputation of Grinnell and for
the quite remarkable loyalty of
its alumni and friends?’ As I
have thought over this ques—
tion, I have reached Several
tentau've answers.

“G r i n n e I l’s reputation is
based in part, I think, on the
continuous Stream of talented
students it has attracted, on the
scholarly attainments of its
faculty, and on the exceptional
distinction of its alumni. But
beneath these outward signs,
the true source of its strength,
I think, has been its constant
dedication to the liberal arts,
its devotion to freedom of in
quiry and freedom of speech,
its consistent practice of de-
mocracy in every day campus
life, its concern for each indi-
vidual students as a distinctive
person, and the essential whole-
someness of its social life. And
I think Grinneii has been able to
hold fast to its principles be

Dr. Howard R. Bowen made
the following statement yester-
day afternoon at his press con-
ference in the library viewing
room:

“The State University of Iowa
is one of America’s great uni-
versities 4 one in which the
people of Iowa justly take great
pride. I am, of course, honored
to be elected as president. and
humbled by the responsibility
placed upon me.

“I look forward to my duties
especially because of my for-
mer association with the uni-
versity where I was a student
and faculty member for nine
years.

“At the same time, I leave
Grinneil College with deep re-
gret a n d great affection.
Grinneli is one of our coun-
try’s outstanding liberal arts
colleges. Through my expe-
rience in both public and pri-
vate colleges and universities,
I hope I may be instrumental
in establishing close ties be-
tween the State University
and the private colleges and
universities of Iowa and other
states.

“I seek support and coopera-
tion for the university from the
people of Iowa. An excellent

university is a cultural and eco-
nomic asset of the first order.
It is one of the prime require-
ments of a state and nation that
intends to develop culturally
and economically. I anticipate
that the State University of
Iowa will occupy a steadily in-
creasing role in the develop
ment of Iowa and the nation.”

 

