When the present problems are
solved, as I am sure they will
be, they will be replaced by
other problems. A lively, vital
college always has problems.
Awareness of them is a symp-
tom of the urge to improve. By
analyzing and facing up to our
problems, we are able to direct
0 ur efforts intelligently. I
earnestly hope that we shall
never be without problems, be;
cause problems represent a
kind of creative dissatisfaction
that will spur us on to build a
greater college.

“50, I, for one, approach the
coming years with a sense 01
confidence. This confidence is
based on the great traditions of
this institution. and on the fact
that we are Stimulated to con-
structive action by the aware-
ness of problems.

At commencement the new
president commented, “I shall
be learning about my new joli
while Working at it fulltime.
During the summer there are
many things to be done around
a College — even though the
students are gone. There are
problems of Staff recruitment.
finances. admissions, and prep-
aration for the opening of the
autumn semester."

